{
  "text": "To assess the likelihood that englacial reflectors in RES data are entrained sediments, we apply Mie theory [CITATION_1] to quantify the sediment grain sizes required to produce the observed echo powers and compare these estimates to surface sediment grain sizes from Patriot Hills, recorded by Westoby et al. (2015) . Under this model, entrained sediment is treated as a random collection of spherical particles of some mean radius occupying some fraction of the ice volume. The total power received by the radar is then the sum of the power backscattered by every particle in the illuminated volume [CITATION_2] . Knowing the echo power, radar system parameters and flight geometry, we set the fractional volume and solve the volumetric radar equation [CITATION_3] for the Mie backscatter coefficient, a function of particle size and material. An open source Mie solver [CITATION_4] was used to invert for the estimated particle radius. Further details of these methods, particularly the radiometric calibration of the radargrams and associated uncertainties, are described in Supporting Information.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "125545942",
    "[CITATION_2]": "60045715",
    "[CITATION_3]": "60045715",
